  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Facing Africa - Correction of facial disfigurements</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="3">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Children and adults with facial disfigurements</narrative>
  </description>
  <description type="1">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Facing Africa funds two teams of highly skilled and experienced volunteer surgeons from the UK, Germany, France and Holland to Ethiopia each year to perform complex facial reconstructive surgery on the victims of the bacterial flesh-eating disease Noma. Each team is made up of 4 surgeons (plastic, maxillo-facial and cranio-facial), 3 anaesthetists, an anaesthetic assistant, 3 operating room nurses, 3 ward nurses, a doctor and 2 wound care nurses. Each surgical mission spends 2 weeks in Ethiopia and generally carries out 35 &#x2013; 45 facial reconstructions.</narrative>
  </description>
